The start symbol S can only expand in one of two ways:

1. S → NT61 NT59  
   – NT59 is a single terminal token, either t46 or t35.  
   – Therefore the last token of any string derived by this rule must be t46 or t35.

2. S → NT29 NT9  
   – NT9 is either the single terminal t18 or begins with the fixed terminal t96 (because NT9 → NT10 NT17 and NT10 → t96).  
   – Thus any string derived by this rule must end with t18 or contain t96 as the first token generated by NT9.

The given string ends with the token t51 and contains neither t46, t35, t18 nor t96 in the required positions.

• Because the string’s final token is t51, it cannot come from the first alternative (which would require t46 or t35).  
• Because the string lacks the necessary endings/lead-ins for NT9, it cannot come from the second alternative.

Hence the grammar cannot generate the provided string.

No

The start symbol S has only two productions:

1. S → NT61 NT59  
   • NT59 is lexical and can produce only t46 or t35 (one token).  
   • Therefore any string derived via this rule must end with t46 or t35.  
   • The given string ends with t62, so this rule cannot generate it.

2. S → NT29 NT9  
   • NT29 can produce  
        – t87 (single token)  
        – t62 (single token)  
        – NT14 NT86  → (t2 | t48)(t0 | t9)(t19 | t5)   (exactly three tokens, all beginning with t2 or t48).  
   • Consequently, any string derived via this rule must begin with t87, t62, t2, or t48.  
   • The given string begins with t46, so this rule also cannot generate it.

Since neither of the only two possible derivations from S can match the required first or last tokens of the provided string, the string cannot be produced by the grammar.

No

The grammar has only two start-rules:

1. S → NT61 NT59  
   – NT59 is a pure terminal producer (‘t35’ or ‘t46’).  
   – Hence NT59 can yield only one token, namely the last token of the string.  
   – The last token in the string is t35, so NT59 would have to produce that and NT61 would have to produce the remaining 33 tokens.

   NT61, however, can produce either  
   • the single terminal t36, or  
   • NT33 NT55, where NT55 is again a pure terminal producer (‘t19’ or ‘t5’).

   Therefore, if NT61 were to cover the first 33 tokens, the 33rd token must be either t19 or t5 (coming from NT55).  
   In the given string the 33rd token is t19, so NT55→’t19’ is forced and NT33 has to cover the first 32 tokens.

   NT33 can expand only as  
   • NT32 NT72  (NT72 is a single terminal t30 or t49), or  
   • NT79 NT22.

   The first 32 tokens contain neither t30 nor t49, so the NT32-NT72 option is impossible.  
   Thus NT33 must be NT79 NT22, so NT79 must cover some non-empty prefix of the 32 tokens and NT22 the corresponding suffix.

   Examining all possibilities shows that NT22 can start only with token t64 (because the leftmost non-unit choice for NT2 in NT22→NT2 NT67 is the single terminal ‘t64’).  
   In the string the only t64 is token 21, so NT22 would have to begin at position 21.  
   Detailed checking of every alternative for NT67 (NT57 NT14, NT29 NT87, NT31 NT28) over the substring 22…32 fails: none of those three patterns can match that substring (they require terminal patterns such as “… t48”, “… t63 t2” preceded by an impossible two-token NT7, etc.).

   Consequently NT22 cannot generate the required suffix, so NT33 cannot generate the first 32 tokens, so the whole derivation under S → NT61 NT59 is impossible.

2. S → NT29 NT9  
   – If NT9→’t18’, the string would have to end in t18, but it ends in t35.  
   – The only other choice NT9→NT10 NT17 forces token t96 immediately before the final block generated by NT17.  NT17 ends either with t64 (NT46 NT54) or with t35/t46 preceded by t18 (NT9 NT59).  Neither alternative fits the last two tokens “… t19 t35”.

Thus neither start rule can derive the given sequence. The string is therefore not in the language of the grammar.
